[2026-03-11 16:13:34] [2af70804-fa0b-4856-a1cd-614d4036a0c3] CLAUDE: ## Review Summary  2 actionable items:  | # | File | Issue | |---|---|---| | 1 | `console.ts:74` | `bridge.send()` is fire-and-forget without `.catch()` — add defensive `.catch(() => {})` to make intent explicit | | 2 | `bridge.ts:7` | `MAX_SEEN = 256` has no comment explaining the choice |  The rest are informational (known fragilities of scraping Meet DOM, `addBounded` test nesting). Want me to fix these two? 
[2026-03-11 16:14:07] [2af70804-fa0b-4856-a1cd-614d4036a0c3] USER: Do we still need MAX_SEEN? 
[2026-03-11 16:14:23] [2af70804-fa0b-4856-a1cd-614d4036a0c3] CLAUDE: Yes, but for a different reason now. The ID-based dedup (`seenIds`) still guards against the MutationObserver firing multiple mutations for the same confirmed message (e.g., parent node restructuring adds a subtree containing an already-processed message). The debug logs showed 14-22 mutations per batch — the same confirmed `div` can appear in multiple `addedNodes`.  `MAX_SEEN` bounds that Set so it doesn't grow indefinitely during a long meeting. Without it, a 3-hour call with hundreds of messages would accumulate entries forever.  So `seenIds` + `addBounded` are still useful. Want me to just add a comment on `MAX_SEEN` and the `.catch()`, then commit? 
[2026-03-11 16:16:05] [2af70804-fa0b-4856-a1cd-614d4036a0c3] USER: Actually there is no reasons for the size of MAX_SEEN. it's just 2^8. 
